{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"303c2e2e-d1e8-474f-aff7-f0720573dcf9","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01TT9mokyGdwRUSRuJuForFs","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Configuring .NET crash dumps"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_012icw7kVzWSdATuTxmto8TT","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"ls -la /tmp/sv-9e207fb2857d49dc92e1de8ead6f2218/ 2>/dev/null; echo \"---\"; dotnet --version 2>/dev/null || echo \"no dotnet\"","description":"Check workspace and environment","initial_wait":10},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Check workspace and environment"}],"interactionId":"b151ef85-b723-48b5-a63f-21c5e296fb32","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to configure automatic crash dump collection for a NativeAOT .NET 11 app running in Kubernetes. They have `createdump` at `/opt/tools/createdump`. Let me look at what's in the current working directory first, and also search for any relevant .NET or Kubernetes configuration files.\n\nActually, the user is asking me to:\n1. Configure the .NET environment variables for automatic crash dump collection with createdump\n2. Provide the Kubernetes pod spec changes needed\n\nLet me think about what's needed:\n\nFor .NET crash dump collection with NativeAOT, the relevant environment variables are:\n\n\n- `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1` to enable crash dumps\n- `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4` for full memory dumps\n- `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/tmp/coredumps/%e.%p.%t.dmp` to set the output path with process and timestamp variables\n- `DOTNET_CreateDumpDiagnostics=1` for additional diagnostics\n- `DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath=/opt/tools/createdump` to point to the createdump tool location since it's not in the standard PATH\n\nFor NativeAOT apps in .NET 8+, these same environment variables control crash dump generation, though the createdump integration works differently since NativeAOT doesn't include the full runtime. The key difference is that `DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath` becomes essential because NativeAOT apps need to know where to find the createdump tool independently.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the Kubernetes configuration needed to support this—I'll need to set those environment variables on the container, provision a volume for storing the dumps, potentially adjust ulimit settings, and ensure the `SYS_PTRACE` capability is available so createdump can attach to the process.\n\nWriting the pod spec YAML...","outputTokens":829,"requestId":"4193:11463F:62DEF16:6C17DF6:69F1632C"},"id":"26176bfe-d443-493c-84ee-b86d0fa8eba0","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:47:42.705Z","parentId":"03948bec-1525-498b-9058-9239fe3a6fc0"}
